</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Pavia 1976" authorityName="Pavia" authorityYear="1976" box="[499,768,188,213]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nitida">
<emphasis box="[499,626,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Bela nitida</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Pavia" box="[637,768,188,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Pavia, G. (1976) I molluschi del Pliocene inferiore di Monteu Roero (Alba, Italia NW). Bollettino della Societa Paleontologica Italiana, 14, 99 - 175." type="journal article" year="1976">
Pavia 
<number box="[709,768,188,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="1976.0">1976</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ardovini 2008" authorityName="Ardovini" authorityYear="2008" box="[783,1093,188,213]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="africana">
<emphasis box="[783,913,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. africana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ardovini" box="[923,1093,188,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Ardovini, R. (2008) Bela africana n. sp. (Gastropoda Turridae) West Africa, Senegal. Malacologia 58, 12 - 13." type="journal article" year="2008">
Ardovini 
<number box="[1035,1093,188,212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ardovini 2004" authorityName="Ardovini" authorityYear="2004" box="[1108,1380,188,213]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis box="[1108,1202,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. exilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ardovini" box="[1212,1380,188,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Ardovini, R. (2004) Due nuove specie e una nuova sottospecie di Turridae da Senegal. Malacologia 43, 7 - 9." type="journal article" year="2004">
Ardovini 
<number box="[1324,1380,188,212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Tucker" box="[151,297,223,248]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Tucker, J. K. (2004) Catalog of Recent and fossil turrids (Mollusca: Gastropoda). Zootaxa, 682, 1 - 1295." type="journal article" year="2004">
Tucker 
<number box="[241,297,224,248]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Mariottini" box="[361,616,223,248]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Mariottini, P., Di Giulio, A., Smriglio, C. &amp; Oliverio, M. (2008) Notes on the Bela brachystoma complex, with description of a new species (Mollusca, Gastropoda,; Conidae). Aldrovandia, 4, 3 - 20." type="journal article" year="2008">
Mariottini 
<emphasis box="[487,548,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[560,616,224,248]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
for iconographic references), even though often referred to 
<taxonomicName box="[1332,1383,223,248]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1332,1383,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Bela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are dubiously attributed to it (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Mariottini" box="[498,743,260,285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Mariottini, P., Di Giulio, A., Smriglio, C. &amp; Oliverio, M. (2008) Notes on the Bela brachystoma complex, with description of a new species (Mollusca, Gastropoda,; Conidae). Aldrovandia, 4, 3 - 20." type="journal article" year="2008">
Mariottini 
<emphasis box="[619,675,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[682,743,260,284]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). These species have very small shells (shell height &lt;
<quantity box="[1348,1423,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="10.0">10mm</quantity>
), with protoconch ornamentation similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[717,826,295,320]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[717,826,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except the sculpture on the last protoconch whorl is stronger, the tubercles are pointed at the intersection with the axials, and extend over more of the surface. With respect to 
<taxonomicName box="[268,404,367,392]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[268,404,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Bela nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the teleoconch of 
<taxonomicName box="[622,796,367,392]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Pleurotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brachystoma">
<emphasis box="[622,796,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">P. brachystoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allied species (what we subsequently refer to as the ‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[160,341,404,429]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Pleurotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brachystoma">
<emphasis box="[160,341,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. brachystoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group’) is characterized by inflated whorls separated by a deep suture that gives the spire a cyrtoconid-turriculate profile. In addition, the sculpture is more pronounced than in 
<taxonomicName box="[1110,1219,439,464]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[1110,1219,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allied species, especially the spiral elements, which are more widely spaced, less numerous and more variable in thickness (i.e., very thin on the subsutural ramp and thicker below the shoulder). The aperture of 
<taxonomicName box="[1080,1253,511,536]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Pleurotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brachystoma">
<emphasis box="[1080,1253,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">P. brachystoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also peculiar, with a sub-rectangular outline and a very thin, almost transparent, outer lip. For anatomical features see 
<bibRefCitation author="Fretter" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Fretter, V. &amp; Graham, A. (1985) The prosobranch molluscs of Britain and Denmark. Part 8 - Neogastropoda. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 15 (Supplement), 508 - 556. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1002 / iroh. 19720570626" type="journal article" year="1985">
Fretter &amp; Graham (
<number box="[256,314,583,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="1985.0">1985</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation box="[377,638,583,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Mariottini, P., Di Giulio, A., Smriglio, C. &amp; Oliverio, M. (2008) Notes on the Bela brachystoma complex, with description of a new species (Mollusca, Gastropoda,; Conidae). Aldrovandia, 4, 3 - 20." type="journal article">
Mariottini 
<emphasis box="[498,547,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[569,631,584,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2008.0">2008</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
Additional species within the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[611,663,620,645]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[611,663,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Bela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Tucker" box="[723,866,620,645]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Tucker, J. K. (2004) Catalog of Recent and fossil turrids (Mollusca: Gastropoda). Zootaxa, 682, 1 - 1295." type="journal article" year="2004">
Tucker 
<number box="[810,866,620,644]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
for references) that share features that are distinct from those of members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[500,609,655,680]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[500,609,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group include a set of fossil species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Brugnone 1862" authorityName="Brugnone" authorityYear="1862" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Pleurotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nevropleura">
<emphasis box="[1041,1317,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Pleurotoma nevropleura</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Brugnone" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Brugnone, G. A. (1862) Memoria Sopra Alcuni Pleurotomi Fossili dei Dintorni di Palermo. F. Lao, Palermo, 41 pp." type="book" year="1862">
Brugnone 
<number box="[151,210,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="1862.0">1862</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bellardi 1847" authorityName="Bellardi" authorityYear="1847" box="[220,614,692,717]" class="Gastropoda" family="Raphitomidae" genus="Raphitoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="plicatella">
<emphasis box="[220,455,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Raphitoma plicatella</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bellardi" box="[461,614,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Bellardi, L. (1847) Monografia delle Pleurotome fossili del Piemonte. Stamperia Reale, Torino, 119 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 58977" type="book" year="1847">
Bellardi 
<number box="[558,614,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="1847.0">1847</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Bellardi 1847" authorityName="Bellardi" authorityYear="1847" box="[667,961,692,717]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hispidula">
<emphasis box="[667,802,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">R. hispidula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bellardi" box="[808,961,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Bellardi, L. (1847) Monografia delle Pleurotome fossili del Piemonte. Stamperia Reale, Torino, 119 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 58977" type="book" year="1847">
Bellardi 
<number box="[905,961,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="1847.0">1847</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[975,1052,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1856,1878]" captionTargetBox="[240,1356,195,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[240,1357,195,1839]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Optical microscope photos of teleoconch features; scale bars 1 mm. A – C) Bela fuscata (Deshayes, 1835) sensu Nordsieck (1977), from Punta Ala (Grosseto, Italy). D) Bela brachystoma (Philippi, 1844) from Djerba (Tunisia), and (F – G) from Porto Azzurro (Leghorn, Italy). G – I) † Bela hispidula (Bellardi, 1847) from Formello Quarry (Rome, Italy). J – L) Mangelia striolata Risso, 1826 from Procida Island (Naples, Italy). SEM photos of protoconch features; scale bar 0.1 mm. M) B. fuscata from Punta Pioppeto (Naples, Italy). N) B. brachystoma from Elba Island (Grosseto, Italy). O) † B. hispidula from Ca’ Lametta (Bologna, Italy). P) M. striolata from Djerba (Tunisia). Symbol: † fossil." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287444/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
Figs. 
<number box="[1038,1052,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
G–I, 
<collectingCountry box="[1109,1132,692,716]" name="Iceland" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">O</collectingCountry>
). These species have larger shell dimensions in comparison to members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[717,824,727,752]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[717,824,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group; however, shell height is commonly less than 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
. The protoconch ornamentation is comparable to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[829,1005,764,789]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Pleurotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brachystoma">
<emphasis box="[829,1005,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. brachystoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, but with weaker sculpture. The teleoconch shape is distinct from that of the previous groups (i.e., 
<taxonomicName box="[931,1041,799,824]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[931,1041,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1103,1279,799,824]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Pleurotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brachystoma">
<emphasis box="[1103,1279,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">P. brachystoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups). The teleoconch profile is generally biconic, the whorls are depressed to slightly concave above the angular periphery, flat-sided below, resulting in a markedly turriculate spire profile. The suture is linear, bordered by a narrow subsutural collar (like in 
<taxonomicName box="[444,555,908,933]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[444,555,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The axial sculpture is more pronounced and generally sharper than in the previous groups. The spiral ornamentation is denser and stronger than in the 
<taxonomicName box="[1004,1110,943,968]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nebula">
<emphasis box="[1004,1110,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">B. nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, composed of cords of very irregular strength, usually deeply indented by growth lines, most conspicuously so below the periphery (such as in the 
<taxonomicName box="[257,431,1015,1040]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Pleurotoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brachystoma">
<emphasis box="[257,431,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">P. brachystoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group). The aperture is elongate and narrow to relatively wide; the outer lip is thin and smooth inside, and the anal sinus is on the shoulder slope, relatively wide, but shallow; compared to the previous groups. The siphonal canal is longer than in previous groups.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
With this stricter definition proposed for the genus 
<emphasis box="[811,868,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName box="[811,865,1124,1149]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Bela</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and the designation of a 
<typeStatus box="[1180,1269,1125,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">neotype</typeStatus>
for the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[151,259,1159,1184]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Mangelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,259,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Mangelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[265,313,1161,1185]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName box="[418,551,1159,1184]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Mangelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="striolata">
<emphasis box="[418,551,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">M. striolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[567,645,1159,1184]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1856,1878]" captionTargetBox="[240,1356,195,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[240,1357,195,1839]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Optical microscope photos of teleoconch features; scale bars 1 mm. A – C) Bela fuscata (Deshayes, 1835) sensu Nordsieck (1977), from Punta Ala (Grosseto, Italy). D) Bela brachystoma (Philippi, 1844) from Djerba (Tunisia), and (F – G) from Porto Azzurro (Leghorn, Italy). G – I) † Bela hispidula (Bellardi, 1847) from Formello Quarry (Rome, Italy). J – L) Mangelia striolata Risso, 1826 from Procida Island (Naples, Italy). SEM photos of protoconch features; scale bar 0.1 mm. M) B. fuscata from Punta Pioppeto (Naples, Italy). N) B. brachystoma from Elba Island (Grosseto, Italy). O) † B. hispidula from Ca’ Lametta (Bologna, Italy). P) M. striolata from Djerba (Tunisia). Symbol: † fossil." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287444/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
Figs. 
<number box="[631,645,1160,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
J–L, P) by 
<bibRefCitation box="[770,1087,1159,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Spada, G. &amp; Della Bella, G. (2010) Identification of Mangelia striolata, type species of the genus Mangelia Risso, 1826. Bollettino Malacologico, 46, 76 - 83." type="journal article">
Spada &amp; Della Bella (
<number box="[1018,1079,1160,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2010.0">2010</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, differences between the allied (and sometime interchanged) genera become clearer.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="51" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
In 
<taxonomicName box="[228,335,1231,1256]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Mangelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[228,335,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Mangelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the outer lip is thickened by a varix externally and internally thickened by a callus extending over the outer lip or forming a bulge in the proximity of the anal sinus. The anal sinus is well-developed in most species, C-shaped, and placed subsuturally (
<figureCitation box="[570,652,1303,1328]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1856,1878]" captionTargetBox="[240,1356,195,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[240,1357,195,1839]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Optical microscope photos of teleoconch features; scale bars 1 mm. A – C) Bela fuscata (Deshayes, 1835) sensu Nordsieck (1977), from Punta Ala (Grosseto, Italy). D) Bela brachystoma (Philippi, 1844) from Djerba (Tunisia), and (F – G) from Porto Azzurro (Leghorn, Italy). G – I) † Bela hispidula (Bellardi, 1847) from Formello Quarry (Rome, Italy). J – L) Mangelia striolata Risso, 1826 from Procida Island (Naples, Italy). SEM photos of protoconch features; scale bar 0.1 mm. M) B. fuscata from Punta Pioppeto (Naples, Italy). N) B. brachystoma from Elba Island (Grosseto, Italy). O) † B. hispidula from Ca’ Lametta (Bologna, Italy). P) M. striolata from Djerba (Tunisia). Symbol: † fossil." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287444/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
Figs. 
<number box="[638,652,1304,1328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
K–L). The axials tend to be thin (smaller than interspaces), sharp, slightly sinuous with maximum curvature in their upper part. In 
<taxonomicName box="[869,920,1340,1365]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[869,920,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Bela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the outer lip is thin, lacking an external varix and smooth internally; the axial sculpture is composed of broad, rounded ribs, usually wider than their interspaces. In contrast, in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[425,477,1412,1437]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Bela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[425,477,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Bela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the anal sinus is shallow, v-shaped and placed on the subsutural ramp. There are also small differences in the protoconch sculpture: on the last protoconch whorl in 
<taxonomicName box="[1068,1175,1447,1472]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mangeliidae" genus="Mangelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
